snippet.textDisplay:
A feature was briefly shown but not discussed during the video. It looks like the A500 was designed with corsair memory in mind since it physically clears corsair designed DIMMs. Not all coolers do this, for example the fan on my NH-U14S conflict badly with one of the second DIMM slots when operating in a blow through configuration. on such a cooler, in order to use all memory one would have to change it to operate in a suck through configuration (fan on other side) which also rules out the option of a dual fan (blow and suck through) installation.

The noise test does not sound like it was entirely fair. Like Gamer's Nexus does, one has to do either a noise normalized comparison and check the temperatures or a thermal normalized comparison and check the noise to know how well it performs. This is because different fan designs have different maximum air flow rates at maximum speed, and even have entirely different maximum speeds. Although it will likely still lose to the competition, it probably would not sound like a jet engine while doing so.
